Msg.Desc: Design contains no %s components eligible for export. Only placed components may be exported.
Msg.ExtDesc:
Because the die and BGA text files define both logical and physical information, you can export only the placed components that have an associated symbol instance. To export an unplaced component, first place it somewhere in the physical drawing layout and run the Die Text-Out wizard again.
If the database has a placed component of the correct type, use the show element command to check the component class of the item that you are exporting. The component class must be "IO" for BGA components and "IC" for die components.

Msg.ExtDesc: Scribe line information affects the size of the die symbol. It is the difference between the drawn die in an IC layout tool and the size of the manufactured component after it has been cut from the wafer using a scribing process.

Msg.Desc: An optical shrink was applied to the exported symbol.
Msg.ExtDesc:
When importing a die component, this tool is able to apply an optical shrink to the physical symbol definition. This will cause all pieces of the symbol definition to be shrunk by the percentage specified. This can lead to multiple original values mapping to the same value because of the numerical scaling and maximum database accuracy.
Due to this potential for rounding and numerical conversion errors, the die symbol will be exported as it is currently represented in the database (after the optical shrink). If this component is read into another package design, do not apply the optical shrink again.

Msg.Desc: The highlighted cell does not meet the requirements for the column header type.
Msg.ExtDesc: To correct this error, perform one of the following tasks: 1. Change the column header type if it was configured incorrectly by the tool. 2. Ignore this row if it represents a comment or data that should not be imported. 3. Exit the wizard and edit the text file to correct the data.

Msg.Desc: Duplicate pin numbers found. The first duplicate pin number has been highlighted.
Msg.ExtDesc:
Each physical pin number must be unique within a component definition or symbol definition. Duplicate pin numbers are not allowed.
Correct this situation as follows: 1. If this is a result of a line occurring twice in your file, mark the second line to be ignored by placing an 'x' in the first column for the line. 2. If a pin number is used twice for two different physical pins, exit the wizard and change the data file, then run the wizard again.

Msg.Desc: The value changed from %s to %s.
Msg.ExtDesc: The original value for this field required adjustment to ensure that the resulting symbol definition would meet the necessary database requirements. The symbol definition must encompass all pins of the symbol and the symbol must be located within the extents of the current drawing.

Msg.Desc: The symbol name is already in use. This value must be unique across all symbol definitions in the design. Enter another name.

The user interrupted the data import process.
Msg.ExtDesc:
If you click the "'stop" button during the import of a text file, the process is interrupted so that you can regain control of the system. Text files, even large files, import quickly. If the import takes a long time, the database may not be configured correctly for the chosen text file.
If your file import is taking a long time, check the following: 1. Pin-to-pin DRC spacing requirements are set to values that are compatible with the data being imported. 2. The correct database units were selected on the first page of the wizard. Set the units to those of the text file, not of the destination database, and the tool will perform any numerical conversions. 3. If padstacks are referenced from the current database or library, the existing padstack definition may not be compatible with the file being imported.

Msg.Desc: Illegal scribe value for %s side. Value must be greater than or equal to 0.0.
Msg.ExtDesc: The scribe values define the remaining material after a die has been cut from the wafer in the die manufacturing process. You cannot use a negative value because it would imply that the scribing action removed material from the manufactured die component.

Msg.Desc: The file contains invalid pin grid definitions. These grids will be ignored.
Msg.ExtDesc:
The die and BGA text files contain specialized lines, usually at the bottom of the file, which define the pin-editing grid structures that are created for use in the Die and BGA editor environments.
These lines are written by the tool on a text export and may not be edited by the user.
To correct this problem, load the symbol into the appropriate editor after completing your text file import, and reconstruct the missing grids.

MCM Import generates a new SIP design from an MCM. For data changes, see extended help.
Msg.ExtDesc:
WARNING: The MCM Import command will create a new SIP design based on the selected MCM database. It does not import into your current design.
During this process, die stacks will be created and all dies added to appropriate stack groups. If not already configured, you will be asked to define the starting and ending layer for your package substrate, with any die layers existing outside the substrate boundary. Full details of any conversions performed will be detailed in the log file.
Do you wish to proceed?

Msg.Desc: BRD Import generates a new MCM design from a BRD. For data changes, see extended help.
Msg.ExtDesc:
WARNING: The BRD Import command will create a new MCM design based on the selected BRD database. It does not import into your current design.
Through this conversion process, objects may be modified to convert them from valid PCB design objects into package objects. Unsupported objects will not be permitted through the conversion process. Full details will be provided in the log file after your conversion is performed.
If not already configured, you will be asked to set up your top and bottom substrate layers before proceeding further.
Do you wish to proceed?

Msg.Desc: MCM Export generates a new MCM design from a SIP. For data changes, see extended help.
Msg.ExtDesc:
WARNING: The MCM Export command will create a new MCM design based on the active SIP database; it does not incrementally update an existing MCM.

Flip-chip %s has been moved from layer %s to layer %s to match die stack cavity/substrate placement settings.
Msg.ExtDesc:
A flip-chip die component needs to have its pads on either a package substrate layer, such as the top or bottom layer (or an internal layer if the die stack is placed in a cavity). It may only be placed on a DIESTACK type layer outside the substrate if it sits above another die or interposer symbol which provides pads for the flip-chip to connect to and a means of connectivity from those pads to the substrate.
For this reason, if you create a flip-chip die as the bottom object (closest to the substrate) of a die stack, its pads will automatically move to the appropriate substrate layer based on the die stack's configured surface / cavity placement settings.

Msg.ExtDesc:
When trying to open and setup the OpenAccess database's library definition list from the file you specified (or a default file found in the current working directory) an error occurred. The detailed error message is given in the OpenAccess Import log file.
This may occur because the library definition file (normally called cds.lib, or possibly lib.defs if the file is old) is missing or contains invalid or missing statements. Another possibility that could possibly occur, but only on Windows platform, is that your software environment has not set the OA_PLUGIN_PATH environment variable to point to the location of your cds.lib plugin (see the on-line Help Documentation for details on setting OA_PLUGIN_PATH).
If your OpenAccess library definition file (e.g. cds.lib in the current working directory) has errors, use a text editor to fix them. If the file is missing, locate it with the Browse button on the form and try again.
If you have failed to set OA_PLUGIN_PATH on Windows platform, follow the instructions in the on-line Help Documentation to set it and then restart SiP Layout and try again. Note that the OA_PLUGIN_PATH environment variable should never be set on Linux.

Run Database Check (dbdoctor) to convert all lowercase characters in pin names to uppercase, while preserving the original mixed-case names in the Verilog_Port_Name property on the corresponding component pin definition.

Msg.Desc: Unable to create a backside pin as there are no legal layers to create the pads on.
Wirebond die component is not placed on die stack layer.
Flip-chip die is bottom die of a die stack. It is placed on a layer that does not match die stack cavity/substrate placement settings.
Msg.ExtDesc: A flip-chip die component needs to have its pads on either a package substrate layer, such as the top or bottom layer (or an internal layer if the die stack is placed in a cavity). It may only be placed on a DIESTACK type layer outside the substrate if it sits above another die or interposer symbol which provides pads for the flip-chip to connect to and a means of connectivity from those pads to the substrate.
